    "If F ⊂ P(X), we put F 0 ∶= F ∖ {∅}, F ↓ ∶= {s ∈ P 0 (X)|∃m ∈ F, s ⊂ m} and we denote by F max the set of maximal elements (for inclusion) of F.(iii) If f ∶ X → Y is a map in sets, ie.",
    "a function of domain X and codomain Y, we denote byf the corestriction of f, that is, f ∶ X → f (X) such that f (x) = f (x) (x ∈ X),(iv) If φ ∶ I → J is a function, we denote by φ the natural extension of φ to subsets of I, precisely φ ∶ P(I) → P(J) defined by: φ(s) = {φ(i) ∶ i ∈ s} Complexes and simplicial complexesBy I-complex (or a complex on I) we mean any subset K of P(I).",
    "An element s of K is called a coalition.",
    "The set of all I-complexes, P(P(I)), will be denoted P 2 (I).An I-simplicial complex (or a simplicial complex on I) is an I-complex K such that K ↓ = K. This is equivalent to say that ∅ ∉ K and (s ∈ K, s ′ ⊂ s ⇒ s ′ ∈ K).",
    "Note that for any I-complex K, K ↓ is the smallest simplicial complex on I that contains K 0, called the simplicial complex generated by K. The set of all I-simplicial complexes is denoted SIM(I)."
